{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472441","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472441"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:58:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:58:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1456"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1456","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1456"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.04,0.54,0.05,0.28]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1456"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114701"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1456","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1456"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1456"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96704"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"186"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"6356"},{"type":"tags","id":"8831"},{"type":"tags","id":"9359"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2612"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2791"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10723"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28372"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39911"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42326"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44050"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44868"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48268"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114701","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114701"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 16-year-old boy is brought in to see his general practitioner and describes posterior headaches often worse when he has hay fever and in mornings. He has shooting pain in his neck that radiates down his arms, particularly at the end of a school day. He also has occasional double vision and dizziness, limiting his participation in sport. These symptoms started about 12 months ago but have only become severe in the last couple of months. He is otherwise well with no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital parameters within normal limits. Neurological examination reveals:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E3/5 power in the proximal lower limb muscles, 4/5 in other lower limb muscles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EImpaired pain/temperature sensation: upper limb \u0026gt; lower limb\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProprioception and vibrations sense were unimpaired\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELhermitte\u2019s sign: positive\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGross hearing reduced, Weber\u2019s central, Rinne\u2019s air \u0026gt; bone conduction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDiplopia and nystagmus on eye exam\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA number of tests are arranged, including an MRI (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cerebral and spinal cord metastases","Vertebral artery dissection","Arnold-Chiari malformation","Hydrocephalus","Multiple sclerosis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient describes a complex mixture of neurological symptoms. These, in combination with the imaging which shows syringomyelia (spinal cord cystic lesion) and herniation of cerebellar tonsils, indicate an \u003Cstrong\u003EArnold-Chiari malformation\u003C/strong\u003E as the causative diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis is a congenital (or rarely, acquired following injury) defect in the posterior cranial fossa where there is herniation of the cerebellar tonsils through the foramen magnum (Image). This leads to compression of brainstem structures and neurological symptoms. It can also cause:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ea hypoplastic posterior cranial fossa\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Esyringomyelia (spinal cord cystic lesions)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ebulbomyelia (brain stem cystic lesions)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere are many types but type 1 is the most common and mildest form, often presenting in late childhood if not picked up earlier.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe common symptoms include sub-occipital headaches (worse with coughing/sneezing or morning as intracranial pressure higher), weakness or sensory phenomenom (typically spinothalamic impaired most from central cord compression) in limbs, visual disturbance, hearing loss, and swallowing issues. Signs include limb weakness, sensory loss, diplopia, sensorineural hearing loss (bilateral in this patient), ataxia/nystagmus (cerebellar signs).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDiagnosis is made through MRI or ultrasound in the antenatal period. Treatment is conservative if patient remains asymptomatic, or surgical management aimed at decompression of the brain stem if significantly symptomatic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetastases to the brain and spinal cord \u003C/strong\u003Ewould be very uncommon in a 16-year-old patient without a history suggestive of cancer. While metastases can cause neurological symptoms such as headaches, weakness, and sensory deficits, they typically present with a different pattern of symptoms and neurological deficits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVertebral artery dissection\u003C/strong\u003E can present with symptoms such as posterior headaches, neck pain, and neurological deficits due to ischaemia or emboli. However, it would not explain all the symptoms in this case, particularly the combination of sensory and motor deficits, diplopia, and nystagmus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydrocephalus\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered due to the patient\u0027s symptoms of headaches and dizziness. However, it would not explain all the neurological deficits described, including the sensory and motor impairments, diplopia, and nystagmus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple sclerosis (MS) \u003C/strong\u003Eis a demyelinating disorder that typically presents with a relapsing-remitting course of symptoms, including visual disturbances, motor weakness, sensory deficits, and ataxia. While it can involve various neurological deficits, it would not typically present with the specific combination of symptoms and imaging findings described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Arnold-Chiari malformation is one of the commonest neurological malformations.","Syringomyelia is often associated with Arnold-Chiari malformation and can cause sensory and motor deficits."],"references":["Strayer A. Chiari I malformation: Clinical presentation and management. J Neurosci Nurs. 2001;33(2):90-96. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11326624/","Rosenblum JS, Pomeraniec IJ, Heiss JD. Chiari Malformation (Update on Diagnosis and Treatment). Neurol Clin. 2022 May;40(2):297-307. doi: 10.1016/j.ncl.2021.11.007. Epub 2022 Mar 31. PMID: 35465876; PMCID: PMC9043468. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9043468/","Hidalgo JA, Tork CA, Varacallo MA. Arnold-Chiari Malformation. [Updated 2023 Sep 4]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK431076/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96704"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1456"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"1611"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22124"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"1611","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/1611"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1b70a84d-e883-4cfd-9528-18bdc7ad7dcc.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1b70a84d-e883-4cfd-9528-18bdc7ad7dcc.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":620,"height":600}},{"type":"media","id":"22124","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22124"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/nQe8IUz7Xg4xDHM8ui2k0WklDBWpam.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/nQe8IUz7Xg4xDHM8ui2k0WklDBWpam.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":620,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96704","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96704"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-19T08:48:38+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-19T08:49:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1456"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114701"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","syn